Task 3: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) – How to Complete
Step 1: Choose a Dataset
Select any one dataset:
✅ Iris Dataset (recommended – simple and easy)
OR
Netflix Movies and TV Shows
 For beginners, Iris Dataset is best.
Step 2: Create EDA Notebook
Use Python (Jupyter Notebook / Google Colab).
Import Required Libraries
Copy code
Python
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
Step 3: Load the Dataset
For Iris Dataset:
Copy code
Python
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris

iris = load_iris()
df = pd.DataFrame(iris.data, columns=iris.feature_names)
df['species'] = iris.target
df.head()
Step 4: Basic Data Understanding
Copy code
Python
df.shape
df.info()
df.describe()
 Insight example:
Dataset has 150 rows and 5 columns
No missing values found
Step 5: Distribution of Numerical Features (Histogram)
Copy code
Python
df.hist(figsize=(10,6))
plt.show()
 Insight:
Petal length and width show clear variation
Sepal features are more evenly distributed
Step 6: Categorical Analysis (Count Plot)
Copy code
Python
sns.countplot(x='species', data=df)
plt.show()
 Insight:
All species are equally distributed
Step 7: Box Plot (Outlier Detection)
Copy code
Python
sns.boxplot(data=df.iloc[:, :4])
plt.show()
Insight:
Few outliers are visible in sepal width
Step 8: Correlation Heatmap
Copy code
Python
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.heatmap(df.iloc[:, :4].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.show()
Insight:
Petal length and petal width have strong correlation
These features are important for prediction
Step 9: Important Features for Prediction
Petal length
Petal width
(Highly correlated and useful for classification)
Step 10: Final Summary (Write in Notebook or Report)
Key Findings (Bullet Points):
Dataset is clean with no missing values
Petal features show strong correlation
Boxplots reveal minor outliers
Petal length and width are best predictors
